<h1>BSc (Hons) Sport Coaching & Development</h1>

											
																
		
		
		



		
			<span class="h4_red">UCAS Code:</span> C6X3 BSc/SCD<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Duration:</span> Three years full-time<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Number of Places:</span> Approx. 30<br />	
<br />
		
			<a href="#Intro">Introduction</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Themes">Core Themes</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Career">Career Opportunities</a><br />	
		
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			
					
			<a href="#Entry">Entry Routes</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Prof">Professional Accreditation</a><br />	
<br />		

		
		
		
			
		

		
			
			
			









	
	
		
		
			
		
	




	
	
		
		
			
			
			
		
	



			
				
				
			
			
		

		
		
<br/>


			<h3 id="Intro">Introduction</h3><b>About this course</b><br /><br /><b>Note:  This programme is only available as a top-up programme and entry is only available to Year 2 upwards.</b><br /><br />If your interest in sport lies in the growing field of sport coaching and sport development our programme has been designed for you.<br /><br />Students on the BSc (Hons) Sport Coaching and Development course study both the coaching and development themes. Coaching themes involve the examination of coaching as a process and the concept of leadership. The development side includes policy and practice analysis, both national and local. You use comparative examples of coach education from the UK, USA and Australia to explore coaching models, the humanistic approach to coaching, mentoring, coach assessment and professional behaviour.  You also examine sporting ethics, motivational psychology and talent identification and undertake performance analysis using video and computer technology.<br /><br />If you hold a relevant Higher National Award you can apply to enter directly at an advanced level and upgrade your qualification to BSc (Hons) Sport Coaching and Development.  This programme encourages you to build on the practical focus of your previous award and to acquire the critical research, decision-making and academic skills required of university graduates.<br /><br /><b>What You Study</b><br /><b>Stage 2</b><br />Practical Sporting Activities; Sport Policy; Sport Leadership Skills & Techniques; Physiological Adaptations of the Body; Coaching the Young Athlete; Event Management.<br /><br /><b>Stage 3</b><br />Coaching Process; Sport Development; Social Context of Sport; Sport Psychology; Coaching Placement; Analysis of  Performance; Strength & Conditioning.<br /><br /><b>Stage 4</b><br />Global Coaching & Coach Education; Sport Development Placement; Managing Performance of Athletes & Teams; Talent Identification & Profiling.<br /><br /><b>How You Learn</b><br />The programme involves taking part in and designing practical sports sessions, lectures, small group seminars and private study.  The link between theory and practice enhanced by coaching placements and work-based sport development experience. On average you have 8 lectures, 3 practical sessions and 4 seminars each week.  You will spend around a minimum of 18 hours per week attending classes, in addition you will be required to undertake  an average of 20 hours of private study a week.  <br /><br /><b>How You Are Assessed</b><br />In stages 2, 3 & 4 assessment varies from 100% coursework to a combination of examination and course work in the ratio 50:50. Some modules will involve both practical assessment and work-based assessment.<br /><br/><br/>	
		
		

			<h3 id="Themes">Core Themes</h3>The following themes run throughout the degree. <br /><br />The sociology of sport applies sociological theory to current issues in sport, including ethnicity, nationalism, professionalism and media coverage.  You will appreciate how sport has evolved globally by studying the history of sport and the rise of international sporting movements such as the Olympics, the Tour de France and the FIFA World Cup. Rule making, sportsmanship  group participation and gender issues are also relevant to the social and practical nature of these enquiries.<br /><br />Healthy eating is important for the body to function properly and for athletes to build muscle.  The nutrition theme introduces you to the anatomy and physiology of the digestive system, brain, liver and muscles and how the human body metabolises (anaerobically and aerobically) food and produces energy.  You will also learn how to produce dietary guidelines which promote healthy eating in a range of people, from children to elite performers.<br /><br />The musculo-skeletal system incorporates a study of the structure and function of bones, joints, tendons, ligaments and facia.  These topics provide the foundation for the study of the mechanics and kinetics of human movement within the parameters of well know theories such as Newtonâs Laws of Motion. This allows you to understand how acceleration, force, mass and momentum impact the human body.  The biomechanics theme also introduces the dynamics of angular motion and how injuries (strains, dislocations, fractures) can occur and/or be prevented. The treatment and rehabilitation of injuries and the healing process (physiological and psychological) will also be considered.<br /><br />The are a number of methods by which a sports practitioner can ascertain an individuals overall physiological shape. This includes using, for example, treadmill, stepping, jumping, resistance, blood pressure, body mass and power testing techniques. You will work in pairs or small groups to measure, test and analyse fitness levels.  <br /><br />The coaching theme will  primarily be studied by students following the BSc (Hons) Sport Coaching & Development degree.  Using comparative examples of coach education from the UK, USA and Australia, you will explore coaching models, the humanistic approach to coaching, mentoring and coach assessment and professional behaviour.  The social context of coaching details sporting ethics, the legal responsibilities of a  coach, motivational psychology, developing a personal style and dealing with burnout in athletes.  In your final year you will undertake a substantial investigation into a topic related to sport coaching and produce a 10 000 dissertation.<br /><br />Regular and effective health screening and assessment go a long way to improving the health of the nation. You will discuss the relationship between patients and health practitioners and the services available to people in the UK.  You learn how personality affects the perception of pain and how an individual deals and copes with different types of pain.  Similarly, consideration is given to raising an awareness of the place of exercise in improving the general well being of people with physical, mental or learning disabilities.  Students following the BSc (Hons) Health & Sport Studies study these and other health related topics in some detail as well as completing a dissertation of similar length to the sports coaching students.<br /><br /><br />	
		
		
		 <h3>Specialist Facilities:</h3>Located within the University is a purpose built Human Performance Laboratory complete with running, rowing, fitness testing and weights machines.  Our Human Performance Laboratory is the most modern in Scotland and has facilities for the treatment and rehabilitation of sporting injuries within itâs Sports Injuries Clinic.  Numerous professional sportsmen and women draw on the expertise of our lecturing staff located within this facility.<br /><br />You also have access to high quality facilities. These include the Scottish National Golf Centre and Dundee United Football Clubâs training ground.   Other facilities include Caird Park athletics track and the Dundee Ice Arena, the most modern ice sports facility in Europe.<br /><br /> 

			<h3 id="Career">Career Opportunities:</h3>Sports development officer, coach, outdoor pursuits instructor, fitness consultant, lifestyle manager, sports administrator, lecturer.<br /><br />	

		
